segments.text: First, Mr. Byrd, would you kind of summarize your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, the places where they were born, the date and place of your birth, and the schools you attended before you went to A&M?
My father was James L. Byrd, and he was born on a farm.
near Corinth, Mississippi in 1857.
And my mother's name was Frances Lester Bird, L-E-S-T-E-R.
Excuse me, Smith.
Her maiden name was Smith.
And she was born near Corinth, Mississippi on a farm.
And they moved to Texas.
about 1880, and Dad lived to be 95, and I've forgotten the date of his death.

Mother lived to be 71, and I've forgotten the exact date of her death, but they're buried at Waco, Texas, where we, the children, or the family generally was born and reared near Waco on a cotton farm.
So you were born on a cotton farm?
I was born on a cotton farm, born at Eddy, Texas.
In Falls County, and we bought a farm in Limestone County.
Drove us back to the Beacon County seat, and then after the farm wasn't big enough, so Dad bought a farm at Bruceville, Texas, and built a home.
And we lived there about two years, I believe, and then bought a farm, a 200-acre farm at Hewitt, Texas, near Waco.
And that's where, in 1911, that's where we lived until we all left home and
had her own families.
So how large of a family did you?
We had, I had five brothers and five sisters.
So you had a total of 11 in all.
That's right, and I was next to the, next to the youngest brother, or child, so to speak.
So did you went to school, you completed school in Waco then?
No, I completed school at Hewitt High School, which was a
a rather small high school even in those days, or school.
It was a four-room school about six miles from Waco.
And when I finished high school there in 1916, I tried to join the Army, and I couldn't.
I was too young.
Well, it was not really in 1917.
And I was 16 years old, and I couldn't get the approval of my parents to join the Army, so they sent me to a military school at Arlington.
Texas, which is now University of Texas at Arlington.
But it was a military school belonging to the state of Texas.
I spent two years there.
Academy?
Well, it was, no, it was, well, two years high school and two years junior college, really, is what it was.
Same as John Tarleton today.
Of course, John Tarleton Senior College today.
So you went, what would be the equivalent of two years of junior college at
No, I finished high school at the school and took one year of college.
I was sort of interested in athletics, and the coaches sold me on the idea of staying over.
I did take my freshman college year there.
In Arlington.
And I was in the military.
And that's the reason they sent me up.
My mother and daddy were real smart about this military business.
They knew I'd be satisfied if I got in the uniform, and I was.
And I was...
there two years and then went to Texas A&M in 1920.
So the idea of being in the military was one factor in your going to A&M.
That's right.
Anything else involved in your choice?
No, I think I'd heard so much about A&M and some fellows from my home community had gone to A&M and they were highly appreciative of A&M and I wanted to go to A&M College.
And as far as entering, then, did you have to supply a transcript to your grades?
I think I did, but I did enter as a sophomore or freshman.
You entered as a sophomore?
In classification, and a freshman, of course, my freshman year.
And then I stayed out one year and worked in the oil fields, and then did finish with the class I entered with, the class of 1924.
You entered as a sophomore in 1920.
That's right.
I should have graduated with a class of 23 had I gone right on.
Well, as an entering sophomore, were you subjected to any of the types of things that the freshmen...
I think, really, Charles, I was subjected to more because I probably had lent myself, so to speak, to that because I had been in the military school, and I enjoyed the fun part.
And in fact, I'd been a captain in this military school, and I knew a little bit about military, and I might have been a year more older than most of the freshmen.
In fact, I was.
But I enjoyed all those activities that went on in the rooms and over the campus.
Well, it was just a great experience.
Were you hazed like a freshman?
I was hazed like a freshman, and more so than a lot of the freshmen, because I was in sophomore classes, and I think more sophomores knew me than they would the average freshman.
But you couldn't do any hazing at that point?
No, no, no.
You were a sophomore only as far as the school was concerned.
As far as the school was concerned.
Whereas the military, you were a fish.
I was a fish, a rank fish.
What were your impressions of, obviously you were somewhat familiar with A&M and the military when you arrived.
Was it really kind of what you expected it to be when you got there?
I think it was because of the fact that I knew some fellows who had gone to A&M or who were in A&M at home and they had told me about A&M and I wasn't surprised at all.
It was just wonderful from the first day I got there carrying the trunks up for the sophomores from the depot until I graduated in 1924.
When you arrived there and registered and then were assigned or entered a military company, did you have any choice in the company you were assigned to?
Yes, I did.
And I was encouraged by some troopers, some people in the cavalry, to join that organization, which I did.
So you opted for the cavalry.
I did.
And I liked horses, too.
You stayed in the cavalry all the years.
All the three years I was there.
Did being in the cavalry require more of your time than, say, being in the infantry?
It probably did.
It probably did.
And we had a lot of esprit de corps.
And we had almost the entire basketball team in our troop my freshman year who were members of the cavalry.
I mean, the varsity basketball.
And it was just a great organization.
When you were in the cavalry, did each cadet take care of his own horse?
No.
No, that was done by the military, by the army, the cavalry personnel, the regular cavalry personnel.
They took care of the animals and the equipment.
And we only saw those animals when we drilled.
And how much of the time did you drill?
We drilled two hours a week on horses.
Uh-huh.
Did you also have to do marching drill?
To some extent, yes.
So even though you were ostensibly riders, you had to march some.
That's right, we had to march some, yes.
Would you describe a typical day during the time that you were there?
Well, I think a typical day during the time I was there would be, I've forgotten the time we would get up, but anyway, we'd dress for breakfast.
and had formation for breakfast.
And out in front of, we were in Leggett Hall at that time.
And we would, it was two troops, Troop A and B, I was in A, and we had marched to breakfast.
And then we would return after breakfast, not in formation, and clean our rooms and maybe two or three sophomores' rooms.
and be ready for classes.
And we did not march to Speza Hall for lunch.
You did not?
We did not.
I'm just pretty sure I'm right about that, Charles, but I don't remember all those organizations at noon.
That would have been a change to what it would have been previously.
Did they have most?
Everybody else I talked to earlier than that said they marched to all three meals.
Well, maybe we did.
I know we did the morning meal and the evening meal, and it's possible we did, but I'd forgotten just a little bit about that.
I wasn't 100% sure that we did march to lunch.
And then what did you do in the afternoon?
And, of course, we had classes during those periods of time.
I spent quite a bit of time in the library, and then of course we'd have meetings in various sophomores' rooms my freshman year.
Bull session?
Bull session, maybe a little bit more than that.
But it was all in fun, and I think that was one of the things that caused A&M to be such a fine school insofar as

comradeship is concerned because we were all the sophomores were concerned about us and they wanted us to be they wanted us to stay in school and and they wanted us to study and they did see that we studied you I presume you had a period in the evening which was required study time that's right like we surely did and we had to be in our rooms and and we did have about
I think about three hours.
I believe that's what it was.
You indicated earlier you had spent a good bit of time in the library.
If you wanted to be in the library during that quiet time, did you have to have a special permit to go to the library?
I would get permission from the captain of the troop.
Nothing in writing necessarily?
No, not necessarily.
That's right.
That's all my freshman year.
The sophomores and upperclassmen didn't have those.
I guess they'd go to the library anytime they wanted to.
And then between your, what was it, between your freshman and sophomore year that you dropped out?
No, I dropped out between, see I entered as a sophomore, and it was between my freshman, actually, the first year.
But I dropped out between my sophomore and junior year in classification and worked in the oil fields one summer, or one year.
It was about nine months.
And then went back to school the next fall.
So you entered as a sophomore, and you joined that same.
So you entered as a sophomore in classification.
And when you came back, you were in line with the people who were freshmen.
I was a junior with the people whom I was a freshman with.
OK. How was the food in the mess hall?
Well, I thought the food was all right most of the time.
Of course, my freshman year, I didn't get very much dessert.
Sophomores got that.
But I think it was adequate.
But I think that so many of us are prone to criticize some of those things, and maybe with justification, some of them.
But I had worked in the oil fields, and I'd been to this military school before.
I mean, two years before.
I went to A&M, and I thought the food was just about what you'd expect.
A little bit monotonous at times.
A little bit monotonous at times, that's right, but just about what you'd expect.
We're feeding a great number of people.
A number of people have kind of indicated the highlight was the steak on Thursday.
Did you have steak on Thursday?
Well, I'm not sure about the date, but we did have steak from time to time.
Fortunately, I didn't let her on the varsity, but I did play freshman athletics some,
And I got to eat on the training table, and that's where we had those delicious steaks every evening.
Every evening.
Yeah.
At that training table, say, if you played basketball, did you eat at the training table the whole year or just during basketball season?
No, just during the season.
Seemed to be for all of the other sports.
That's right, all the rest of them, yeah.
I believe you said you were in Milner?
No, Leggett.
Leggett Hall.
Were you in Leggett all the years you were there?
No, I was in Leggett one year and then Mitchell the other two.
Mitchell and the other two.
Yeah.
Was that, well, both of them were relatively new at that point, were they not?
No, Leggett wasn't.
Leggett's one of the old halls.
In fact, I saw that in this book of, I think, Dean Stang was, but it's one of the early halls that was built in an early period.
And Mitchell was later.
And junior and senior year, I was in Mitchell Hall.
That's interesting.
Leggett's still there in Mitchell's, huh?
That's right.
I was going to make that comment.
We were down there last two or three months ago.
Did the upperclassmen, I gather from what you've said, this is true, but the upperclassmen, as a rule, had a good bit more privileges than the freshmen.
They did, yes, sir.
more freedom to move around campus.
What about during that quiet hour?
Did basically all four levels have to be in their room studying?
Well, I think generally they did.
I'm sure the juniors and seniors probably didn't have to adhere to that so strictly as the sophomores and freshmen did.
Some of the upperclassmen or sophomores were just an overgrown freshman.
Did they line you up and march you to chapel on Sunday?
Yes, they did.
In Guyon Hall?
That's right.
Did the seniors have to go, too?
Seniors, maybe one senior from the Troop A cavalry, in my instance, marched all those to Guyon Hall, just one, as I recall.
So most of the seniors skipped out on that?
Yeah, they didn't have to go.
They would alternate on that.
Was that maybe because the core was large enough that there wasn't enough room for all of them?
It could be.
It could be.
At the time that you were there, what could you do for recreation and entertainment?
Well, we had the YMCA.
We could swim.
And we had all those, there's athletics going on all the time, some type of athletics.
Mm-hmm.
And we might be interested in company basketball, or company baseball, or company football.
And of course, there's always some sessions in the various rooms.
Being in the cavalry, we were able to go on some hikes with our horses, riding horses on weekends occasionally when we could get permission to do that.
Now, would this be the whole company or just individuals?
No, it would be just individuals, two or three or four or five individuals.
Just to go kind of check out a horse?
That's right, that's right.
Go for a good ride.
Yeah, that's right.
Okay.
was, this is not really entertainment and recreation, but I believe the year after you graduated was the year that Harold Dunn had his famous hamburger stand on the campus.
But he told me that that stand was there two or three years before that.
It was.
It was near Speeds to Hall, as I recall, and it was a newsstand and a hamburger stand.
News and hamburger combined.
Yeah, when I knew it.
He didn't indicate that he had anything to do with the newspapers.
It might have been magazines.
So that was there for if anybody wanted supplemental food.
Was there still Casey's Confectionery in the basement?
That was a central meeting point.
Somebody had 15 or 25 cents to buy a malted milk.
That was in the basement of the Y.
That's the basement of the Y, and I think the Y is still there.
Yeah, the Y is still there.
The swimming pool is not there.
No.
Nor is the confectionery.
Yeah.
But were there any rooms in the Y that people could stay as there traditionally is in a Y?
Charles, I'm not real sure.
I am not positive about that, but we had Alpha and Beta Hall where people could stay.
And they were located where?
They were located up near Speza.
Now that was before the Aggieland Inn.
Yes, that's right.
So I believe at one point, I understood Alpha and Beta Hall were non-military dorms.
That's right.
Well, they could have been.
Maybe World War I veterans.
I'd rather think those are the fellows who stayed there.
But did they also have rooms that the visitor could stay in?
I'm just sure in alpha and beta because I stayed there two or three times after I graduated from A&M.
I would be at A&M visiting A&M, and I have stayed there.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
Well, I had some real fine instructors that I just loved right on down through the years.
I think Dr. C.C.
Hedges, chemistry department, I enjoyed him very, very much.
And I enjoyed Dr. O.M.
Ball, the head of the botany department.
My major was agronomy.
And I think one reason I appreciated Dr. Ball so much, because being in a sophomore class, my freshman year, I was taking botany my freshman year as a sophomore.
And Dr. Ball recognized the fact that I was being hazed by those sophomores, and I think he's the one professor whom I had a drag with, so to speak.
That's how we expressed it back in those days, because he thought I was being abused by the sophomores.
And it was great fun, but he was a great instructor.
And Dr. Jones in the English department, and Colonel Ike Ashburn, commandant,
I thought he was a grand person, and I admired him greatly, and he was thoroughly capable.
You indicated you had spent a good bit of time in the library.
Did you ever have any contact with Dr. Mayo?
Yes, I did.
English.
I surely did.
And he also was a librarian, I believe.
That's right, he was.
And Captain Davis, I've forgotten his first name and initials, but he was head of the cavalry.
at the time I was there, and he was a great military person.
I admired him a great deal.
He would have been, what, directly under Ike Ashburn?
Well, yes, yes.
I don't know just what Ike's relationship was with the regular military personnel on that campus.
It gets a little vague to me.
He had been out of the military for a number of years.
He had been a colonel, yeah.
But he was commandant of the cadets, of the cadet corps, really.
That was his title.
He would have been a colonel perhaps during the First World War.
Yes.
And then he was out of the military for a while.
That's right.
He was actually a civilian commandant.
That's right.
He was not reappointed to the military.
No, he did not wear a uniform.
But he was very well liked by the students overall.
Greatly appreciated by the students.
He was fair and fine, and being a military man, he stood up tall and sat down.
Tall in the saddle, I'll say, and everybody had a great deal of respect for him.
What about the students' attitude to the president, Dr. Brazell?
Well, Dr. Brazell was one of the fine gentlemen I've known in college or out of college.
He was a great person.
And I know the students respected Dr. Brazell a great deal.
because he was a gentleman and a great educator.
I had always, and I really have no real reason to change my attitude.
In what I had heard and read about Dr. Brazell, I thought he must have been really something, one of the best they've had there for a long time.
I think so.
One of, another former student brought to us, I guess I would call it an underground newspaper called the Longbat that was, I believe, in January of 24.
And I was a little bit puzzled by one of the student editorials in there that indicated they were complaining, I guess, about censorship of student opinions.

And I don't know whether it was in the battalion that there was censorship or what, but anyway, the guy who wrote the editorial said something to the effect that he was complaining about not being able to say what you really thought.

And he said, if you don't believe this is right, why, get up in the middle of the main building and say what you think, and then count how many minutes it is till the next train comes through, and that's how long you have to stay.
Well, I didn't have that feeling about Dr. Brazell or anyone on that campus, and I might not have been that close to him.
Well, I really never did know for sure whether it was Dr. Brazell they were talking about or the commandant or whether they were talking about...
I don't think they were talking about upperclassmen because I understood that it was a group of seniors who got out this issue of the newspaper.
Now, those seniors, would they have been in the class of 24?
I believe so.
I don't remember anything about that.
I believe it was January 24 that they called it.
It was a little bitty thing about, oh, 12, 14 inches tall and about 10 or 11 inches wide.
It was a four-page thing called the long bat.
And I believe they had some things to say about the barbershop, and I believe Charlie Nitchie was still there in the tailor shop.
He was a tailor.
I'm not sure, but they were a little bit unkind to Casey's Confectionery.
Well, I have an idea.
Those boys just wanted to, they were becoming young men, I think, possibly they just wanted to express themselves.
I think that's psychologically a fact many times when we want to criticize something, we just want to launch out.
One of the things that I have thought since I've been in A&M that makes it a,
An interesting institution and different from others is the number of traditions that exist there carried on by the students from year to year.
And I'm thinking in terms of old Yale practice, the silver taps, the bonfire, and things of that nature.
How many of these were in existence during your years there?
Well, those three or four ones that you mentioned were certainly
We had silver taps, and it happened at least twice while I was there.
And we had yell practice, which we thoroughly enjoyed, and I think that was something that brought us together and made us feel as one.
And the general, of course, it was all cadet corps, except the casuals, who were World War I veterans.
My freshman in South Wales,
Not necessarily the World War.
Well, some of them were veterans who had been, stayed out of school a while.
And I know one of my real fine friends was a World War, had been in the Navy in World War I.
And he finished in my class, and he was not in the cadet corps.
And those, but anyway.
He was not in the cadet corps at all.
No, not at all.
And many, and I won't, quite a few weren't in the cadet corps.
And they were not in the cadet corps because of the fact they had served in World War I.
even though it might have been, well, 1920.
Of course, the war was over in 1918.
But I think the Yale practice, and I'm not so sure about the bonfire.
We had some, but not to the magnitude that they do it now.
But we did have a great spirit.
And did you have a muster on April 21st?
I'm just sure we did not.
I don't recall that.
But how about, did you have a holiday?
I'm not real sure about that.
I had understood from what I had been able to find out about the start of that 1903 that the students objected to going to school on Texas Independence Day.
Or is that Texas Independence Day?
Anyway, on that particular date.
And so they sort of declared an unofficial holiday and had a muster, so to speak.
Well, I'm sorry I'm not sure about that, but I'm really not.
We recognized April 21st.
Today we have school, but we have a muster at 5 o'clock.
And it's observed pretty much worldwide, though, by former students.
And I guess it really is more of a former student
ceremony than a student one.

You mentioned a minute ago that the veterans of the First World War were not in the Corps of Cadets, and I think there had always been a number who were physically incapable of carrying out the military duties.
Was there any period during the time that you were there that
that anybody other than the veterans and the physically handicapped could, say, discontinue the Corps after the first couple years?
Charles, I don't think there was.
I just don't think there was.

Somebody I talked to yesterday indicated, well, he dropped out of the Corps after a couple years, but then he said in their senior year, I think he was there for five years, and last year he had to wear a uniform.
For two years, he didn't wear a uniform.
Well, those who...
And I think that came later when they were not given commissions in the junior year.
I mean, they were not qualified to go on and get a commission.
Quite a few of those fellows didn't know anything about that until the end of their senior year.
I know there's several that were still in the cadet corps who did not get
reserve commissions.
This was when you were in school?
When I was in school, that's right.
Was that because they were somewhat deficient in their military interest, I'd say.
I think most anyone could have gotten commission had they been interested enough in military.
Reserve commission.
We know that a number of students throughout the history of A&M have been part-time employees in one form or another.
Did you have any jobs?
I didn't have any jobs, Charles.
I worked in the oil fields a total of nine months in the summer.
You didn't have any part-time jobs?
I didn't have any part-time jobs.
We had a wonderful farm at home, and the family could have sent me to school.
But I wanted to get a little independent, and I did make my way the last two or three years in the oil fields, working in the oil fields.
And I did not work at A&M.
So you worked in the oil fields in the summer?
In the summer, except when I went to two ROTC camps.
Shirley?
